State of South Carolina
Union District

Be it known that on the 23rd day of May AD one thousand eight hundred & fifty seven and in the 81st year of American Independence before me a magistrate in and for said District and State Duly commissioned and sworn came Samuel B Phillips administrator of the Estate

State of South Carolina}
Union District}

Mordecai Chandler Personally appeared before me & deposeth as follows in order to obtain the benefit of the Act of Congress of 7th June 1832.  and to give more explicit Satisfaction to The Terms of his Services during the Revolutionary War— Saith that he Served Twelve month certain and thinks longer on his first enlistment and was regularly discharged before the expiration of his enlistment on account of his having Volunteered & marched to Forida [sic]—  the Second Tour was out four months, [illegible] Capt Jno. Lyles— & the third Tour under Capt Liles four month—  I again served nine months & upwards under Sumpter, Clark & Shelby, before I was taken prisian [sic], I there by in Jail at 96.  a presian [sic] five months precisely, and then Sent to Charleston & put on a prisian [sic] Ship where I remain two months before I was exchanged, I again Served another tour of two months.  & at another Time a Tour

State of South Carolina}
Union District}

I John Rogers Clerk of the Court of Sessions & Common Pleas for Said District do Certify that James Rountree Esqr. is an Acting Justice of the peace and properly authorized to administer oaths that his Signature is genuine—  and his official acts as Such are entitled to full faith & Credit as Such—

Given under my hand & Seal of office at Union Court House this 6 day of May 1833—
J. Rogers  clk

Note:  Bottom left of page is an area covered over but presumed to be Seal of office
